# Express REST API Conventions

## Router structure

- Each feature owns a dedicated router file named `feature.routes.ts` (e.g. `auth.routes.ts`, `users.routes.ts`).
- `src/presentation/http/routes/index.ts` is the central aggregator: it imports every feature router and mounts it with `httpRouter.use("/feature", featureRouter)`. No business logic lives here.
- Mount the central `httpRouter` in `app.ts` under the versioned prefix `/api/v1`.

## Route definition

- Use resource-oriented paths and consistent versioning, such as `/api/v1/users`.
- The standard middleware order for every protected route is: `requireAuth → validateRequest → controller`.
- Public routes omit `requireAuth` but still pass through `validateRequest` when input is expected.
- Keep route handler callbacks in controller files; do not inline business logic inside route files. Only trivial utility routes (e.g. `/ping`) may use inline handlers.

## Controllers

- Keep controllers thin: retrieve validated input via `getValidated`, call the application/service layer, check the `Result`, and map to the appropriate HTTP status code.
- Never access repositories, domain entities, or infrastructure adapters directly from a controller.

## Validation

- Validate request `body`, `params`, and `query` with `zod` schemas at the boundary using `validateRequest`.
- Co-locate each feature's Zod schemas in `presentation/http/validators/feature.validator.ts`.

## Middleware and error handling

- Register the `404` handler after all routes and `errorMiddleware` as the very last middleware in `app.ts`.
- Always call `next(error)` to propagate errors to the centralized error handler; never build ad hoc error responses inside controllers.
- Always call `next()` when a middleware does not end the request-response cycle.

## Response and logging

- Return consistent JSON shapes for success and failure; avoid ad hoc response structures across controllers.
- Use standard status codes intentionally: `200`, `201`, `204`, `400`, `401`, `403`, `404`, `409`, `422`, `500`.
- Use `morgan` for HTTP access logs and keep `cors` configuration centralized in `app.ts`.
